[30;1m13 | [0m[35mools_scm`` takes the current version of the[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35msource from git tags and any additional commits. For development, the version will have a[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mstring like ``0.10.0.post209+gff2e549f.d20190918``, which comes from ``git describe``. This[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mversion means that the current code is 209 commits past the 0.10.0 tag, on git hash[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m``ff2e549f``, with local changes on top, last made on a date (indicated by ``d20190918``). For[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35ma release, or non-git repo source dir, the version will just come from the most recent tag[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m(i.e. ``v0.10.0``). Our main versioning scheme matches ``vMajor.Minor.Bugfix``.[0m

[30;1m11 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mTo manage identifying the version of the code, MetPy relies upon `setuptools_scm[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m<https://github.com/pypa/setuptools_scm>`_. ``setuptools_scm`` takes the current version of the[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35msource from git tags and any additional commits. For development, the version will have a[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mstring like ``0.10.0.post209+gff2e549f.d20190918``, which comes from ``git describe``. This[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mversion means that the current code is 209 commits past the 0.10.0 tag, on git hash[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m``ff2e549f``, with local changes on top, last made on a date (indicated by ``d20190918``). For[0m

[30;1m199 | [0m[35m# However, this "quantification" is not without its consequences. By default, xarray loads its[0m
[30;1m200 | [0m[35m# data lazily to conserve memory usage. Unless your data is chunked into a Dask array (using[0m
[30;1m201 | [0m[35m# the ``chunks`` argument), this ``.quantify()`` method will load data into memory, which[0m
[30;1m202 | [0m[35m# could slow your script or even cause your process to run out of memory. And so, we recommend[0m
[30;1m203 | [0m[35m# subsetting your data before quantifying it.[0m
[30;1m204 | [0m[35m#[0m
[30;1m205 | [0m[35m# Also, these Pint ``Quantity`` data objects are not properly handled by xarray when writing[0m

[30;1m164 | [0m[35m``main``, it's there forever![0m

[30;1m2 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m3 | [0m[35mInterested in helping build MetPy? Have code from your research that you believe others will[0m

[30;1m122 | [0m[35mexpand the set of formats to which MetPy facilitates access. This also fits with filling[0m
[30;1m123 | [0m[35mGEMPAKâ€™s feature set, since its support for a variety of data formats was important to its[0m
[30;1m124 | [0m[35mutility. Unlike GEMPAK, MetPy will never rely on a set of â€œdecodersâ€ to translate datafiles to[0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35ma new format. This goes against the spirit of fitting within the rest of the scientific Python[0m

[30;1m2033 | [0m[35m    * :math:`e'` is vapor pressure[0m
[30;1m2034 | [0m[35m    * :math:`e'_w(T_w)` is the saturation vapor pressure with respect to water at temperature[0m
[30;1m2035 | [0m[35m      :math:`T_w`[0m
[30;1m2036 | [0m[35m    * :math:`p` is the pressure of the wet bulb[0m
[30;1m2037 | [0m[35m    * :math:`T` is the temperature of the dry bulb[0m

[30;1m463 | [0m[35m    The function is guaranteed to finish by virtue of the `max_iters` counter.[0m

[30;1m158 | [0m[35m# ------------------[0m

[30;1m160 | [0m[35m# A hodograph is a polar representation of the wind profile measured by the rawinsonde.[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35m# Winds at different levels are plotted as vectors with their tails at the origin, the angle[0m
[30;1m162 | [0m[35m# from the vertical axes representing the direction, and the length representing the speed.[0m
[30;1m163 | [0m[35m# The line plotted on the hodograph is a line connecting the tips of these vectors,[0m
[30;1m164 | [0m[35m# which are not drawn.[0m
